      <h2 class="section-title">Strategic Observations</h2>
      <div class="section-rule"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-priority critical">01 — Critical</div>
      <div class="insight-heading">The business is in a cash burn phase that cannot be sustained beyond one to two quarters</div>
      <div class="insight-body">Q1 2026 reduced total equity by approximately $203K. At this rate, the business approaches technical insolvency on a net equity basis by mid-year. The AMEX and line of credit are absorbing operating shortfalls, not capital investment. This is not a growth investment pattern; it is a structural mismatch between OPEX expansion and revenue. A 30-day rolling cash flow forecast is the immediate requirement. The conversation with William about spending governance, draw restrictions, and a near-term recovery plan must happen before the Q2 close.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-priority critical">02 — Structural</div>
      <div class="insight-heading">Sales payroll yield has deteriorated: the seminar funnel requires an immediate efficiency review</div>
      <div class="insight-body">Sales payroll of $183.9K in Q1 against $724.9K revenue represents 25.4% COGS-to-revenue, up from 20.1% in FY2025. Advertising spend of $104.7K ($35K per month) is consistent with the seminar model but is producing less Granite income per dollar spent than in prior periods. Either the team has grown without commensurate production, or conversion rates have declined. Cost per seminar attendee, close rate, and average case size are the three metrics that need to be on the table before the next cycle of advertising spend is committed.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-priority structural">03 — Revenue Mix</div>
      <div class="insight-heading">Recurring management fee income is the right long-term lever but is growing too slowly to de-risk the P&amp;L</div>
      <div class="insight-body">Management fee income grew 64% year-on-year in Q1 (from $180K to $295K). This is the right directional signal. But at $295K per quarter, recurring income annualises to approximately $1.18M against a normalised OPEX base of $2.11M annualised. The business needs recurring revenue to cover 70–80% of OPEX to meaningfully reduce earnings volatility. The AUM scenario work (see Section 05) quantifies what is required. The priority is accelerating AUM conversion from existing commission clients who are suitable for ongoing advisory relationships.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-priority structural">04 — OPEX Discipline</div>
      <div class="insight-heading">Professional fees and travel are running at levels inconsistent with current revenue, and require governance</div>
      <div class="insight-body">Professional fees of $113.3K in Q1 alone annualise to $453K, versus $229.6K for the full year 2025. The nature of these fees must be understood: legal, compliance, specialist advisers, or otherwise. Travel at $39.2K in Q1 (with March alone at $25.8K) is sharply above run rate and requires categorical breakdown. Both categories should be subject to monthly approval against a quarterly budget. CT PET Tax at $47K should be confirmed as either a quarterly or annual item — if annual, it should be accrued monthly rather than expensed in lump sum.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="insight-card">
      <div class="insight-priority">05 — Valuation Implications</div>
      <div class="insight-heading">Q1 2026 performance materially impacts enterprise value; the recovery narrative must be built now</div>
      <div class="insight-body">RIA businesses typically trade at 2–4x revenue or 8–12x EBITDA, with material premium for recurring revenue proportion, advisor retention, and operational infrastructure. On FY2025 normalised EBITDA of approximately $1.45M, a 6–8x multiple would imply an $8.7M–$11.6M enterprise value range. One quarter of losses does not destroy that, but a trend does. The strategic synopsis identified founder dependency, limited systems, and commission revenue skew as valuation discounts. Each month of Q1-style performance reinforces all three. The hiring plan, digital marketing transition, management layer, and AUM growth programme are not operational matters; they are the valuation restoration plan.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

